The important thing is, that `trace_write_msr` (using `static_branch_unlikely()`) evaluates the *same* `__do_trace_write_msr` when the tracepoint is **enabled**. So, if `do_trace_write_msr` calls `trace_call__write_msr()`, the only difference is that when the tracepoint is **disabled**, it STILL takes the `tracepoint_srcu` read lock! But I see that, when disabled, it never reaches it. `tracepoint_enabled(write_msr)` in `asm/msr.h` is **false**, and that skips the call to `do_trace_write_msr`.

